1.3.27

(a) Clearly $y(x)$ is differentiable away from $x=c$ with $$ y'(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rl} 0 & \mbox{for } x < c \\ 2(x-c) & \mbox{for }x > c \end{array} \right.$$ but since $\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 0^\pm} y'(x) = 0$ we have $y(x)$ is differentiable for all $x$ with $$ y'(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rl} 0 & \mbox{for } x \leq c \\ 2(x-c) & \mbox{for }x > c \end{array} \right. .$$ The zero function easily satisfies the DE, while the other piece $$ 2(x-c) \overset{?}{=} 2 \sqrt{ (x-c)^2} = 2 |x-c| \overset{x>c}{=} 2(x-c)~ \checkmark$$ does as well.

Clearly $y(x) = 0$ for all $x$ satisfies the DE and $y(0) = 0$, as does $$y(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rl} 0 & \mbox{for } x \leq c \\ (x-c)^2 & \mbox{for }x > c \end{array} \right.$$ for any $c > 0$.

The partial derivative $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} 2\sqrt{y} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{y}}$ is not continuous for $y=0$, and so the Existence and Uniqueness Theorem doesn't apply! We know it can't, since we just saw nonuniqueness!

(b) If $b<0$, then the slope is not defined for the initial data point, and so there is no solution.

If $b > 0$, then $$y(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rl} 0 &\mbox{for }x \leq - \sqrt{b} \\ (x+\sqrt{b})^2 & \mbox{for } x > - \sqrt{b}\end{array} \right.$$ is the unique solution to the DE and initial condition $y(0)=b$.

Since $\frac{\partial}{\partial y} 2\sqrt{y} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{y}}$ is continuous close enough to $(0,b)$ for $b > 0$, the existence and uniqueness theorem applies and guarantees a solution $y(x)$ defined for $x$ near $0$. We see the given formula in fact defines a continuously differentiable solution for all $x$.

In part (a) we deduced that infinitely many solutions satisfy $y' = 2\sqrt{y}, y(0) = 0$, and so if $b=0$ there are infinitely many solutions containing $(0,0)$.

1.4.47

Let $N(t)$ be the number (in thousands) who have heard the rumor at time $t$ (in weeks), so that $100-N(t)$ is the number who have not. Then, $$\frac{dN}{dt} = k(100-N), \quad N(0) = 0, \quad N(1) = 10.$$ (We interpret "rumor starts spreading at $t=0$" means $N=0$ at that time). The DE is separable so we proceed with \begin{align*} dN &= k(100-N) dt, \\ \int \frac{1}{100-N} \, dN &= \int k \, dt,\\ - \ln|100-N| &= kt + C_1,\\ \ln|100-N| &= -kt - C_1, \\ 100-N &= \pm e^{-kt-C_1} = C_2 e^{-kt},\\ -N &= -100 + C_2 e^{-kt},\\ N &= 100 + Ce^{-kt}. \end{align*} We use $N(0) = 0$ to see $$0 = 100 + Ce^{-k(0)} \implies C=-100 $$ making $$N = 100 -100 e^{-kt}.$$ Using $N(1) = 10$ yields $$ 10 = 100-100e^{-k} \implies \frac{9}{10} = e^{-k} \implies k = - \ln \left( \frac{9}{10} \right) = \ln \frac{10}{9} > 0$$ as expected. (Otherwise the number of people knowing the rumor would be decreasing for $N < 100$! Remember $\ln(x) > 0$ for $x > 1$ while $\ln(x) < 0$ for $0 < x < 1$ --- I use this to eliminate unnecessary minus signs and to do sanity checks like this.) Then $$N = 100 - 100 e^{- \ln(10/9) t}$$ and solving $$50 = 100 - 100 e^{-\ln(10/9)t}$$ yields $$ \frac 1 2 = e^{- \ln(10/9) t} \implies t = - \frac{\ln(1/2)}{\ln(10/9)} = \frac{\ln 2}{\ln(10/9)} > 0 $$ also as expected. $\boxed{\mbox{Half the population has heard the rumor after }\frac{\ln 2}{\ln(10/9)}\approx 6.58 \mbox{ weeks }\approx 46\mbox{ days.}}$

1.4.54

The cross section of the tank $A$ is constant with respect to height $y$, and so the volume $V(t)$ satisfies $V(t) = A y(t)$, transforming $$ \frac{dV}{dt} = -k \sqrt{y} \implies \frac{dy}{dt} = -h \sqrt{y}$$ with $h= \frac{k}{A}>0$ the constant of proportionality. All together, we have $$ \frac{dy}{dt} = -h \sqrt{y}, \quad y(0) = 9, \quad y(1) = 4.$$ We are asked to find when $y=0$.

The DE is separable so we proceed with \begin{align*} \int \frac{1}{\sqrt{y}} \, dy &= -h \, dt \\ 2 \sqrt{y} &= -ht + C_1, \\ \sqrt{y} &= -\frac{h}{2}t + C. \end{align*} I'm not going to isolate $y$ since that is not reversible --- we don't want to create any issues with "extraneous" solutions while solving for our parameters. Using $y(0) = 9$ quickly yields $3=C$ and so $\sqrt{y} = -\dfrac{h}{2}t+3$. Then, $y(1) = 4$ yields $$ \sqrt{4} = -\frac h 2+3 \implies h = 2,$$ and so $$ \sqrt{y} = 3-t.$$ We quickly see the tank is $\boxed{\text{drained after 3 hours}}.$

Torricelli's law fails "backward uniqueness" when the tank is empty; actually expected from modeling perspective

For simplicity let's assume that $h$ is fixed at 2 (there are ways to measure it in terms of the cross section area and area of the hole in the tank) so that we can see the expected nonuniqueness while "thinking about different experiments with the same tank". Suppose we have the IVP $$ y' = - 2\sqrt{y}, \quad y(3) = 0.$$ One solution would be the solution considered in the problem, and then continuing as empty: $$ y(t) = \left\{ \begin{array}{lr} (3-t)^2& 0 \leq t \leq 3 \\ 0 & t > 3 \end{array} \right. .$$ Another solution would be $$y(t) = 0 \mbox{ for all } t \geq 0.$$ However, it could have emptied at any time before $0$ and $3$, so that $$ y(t) = \left\{ \begin{array}{lr} (1-t)^2& 0 \leq t \leq 1 \\ 0 & t > 1 \end{array} \right. .$$ also satisfies $y(3) = 0$!

The $\sqrt{y}$ in Torricelli's law that leads to the $y$-partial derivative being discontinuous at $y=0$ prevents the Existence and Uniqueness Theorem from applying to "empty" initial value problems. While we have stated that existence and uniqueness is very important for the validity of a model in predicting nature, this failure here is in fact consistent with what we expect from the modeling in this case. If I only know the tank is empty at $t=3$, it is obvious that's not enough information to uniquely determine the past since perhaps the tank just emptied right at $t=3$, or was always empty, or emptied at $t=1$ and has been empty between $t=1$ and $t=3$, or ...

1.4.65

Detectives/medical examiners probably have to look this up, but we understand the math behind it completely.

Let noon correspond to $t=0$, so that Newton's law for the body temperature $T(t)$ satisfies $$\dfrac{dT}{dt} = k(70-T), \quad T(0) = 80, \quad T(1) = 75.$$ The equation is separable so we proceed with \begin{align*} \int \frac{1}{70-T} \, dT &= k \, dt \\ -\ln|70-T| &= kt + C_1,\\ \ln|70-T| &= -kt + C_2, \\ 70 - T &= \pm e^{-kt + C_2} = C_3 e^{-kt},\\ T &= 70 + C e^{-kt} \end{align*} Using $T(0) = 80$ means $80 = 70 + Ce^0$ so $C=10$, and therefore $$T=70+10e^{-kt}.$$ Using $T(1) = 75$ means $$75 = 70+10e^{-kt} \implies \frac 1 2 = e^{-kt} \implies k = - \ln\frac 1 2 = \ln 2 > 0$$ as expected. (Otherwise, the body would be heating instead of cooling for $T>70$.) All together, $$ T = 70 + 10 e^{-t \ln 2}$$ and so solving $$ 98.6 = 70 + 10e^{-t \ln2} \implies 2.86 = e^{-t \ln 2} \implies t = - \frac{\ln 2.86}{\ln 2} < 0$$ as expected (the time of death should be in the past relative to noon). Therefore, the $\boxed{\mbox{time of death was }\frac{\ln 2.86}{\ln 2} \approx 1.516\mbox{ hours before noon, or at around 10:29AM}}$.

What if the environment wasn't exactly 70$^\circ F$? Provided we know the ambient temperature function $A(t)$, we could rearrange the equation as $$T' + k T = kA(t),$$ which is a first order linear DE! Depending on the form of $A(t)$, the computations may not be as doable by hand as the constant $A$ case; but with the aid of numerical integration and equation solving schemes it wouldn't be a difficult problem.

Slope field problems

See https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1iEGBSHNNllIynPYCeCE4-kmJbQiTNHYE?usp=sharing to interact with the code for the solutions to the additional slope field problems from Google Colab.

Problem 1

(From the Edwards and Penney text, problem 1.3.26) Suppose the deer population $P(t)$ in a small forest satisfies the logistic equation

$$\dfrac{dP}{dt} = 0.0225P - 0.0003P^2.$$

Construct a slope field and appropriate solution curve to answer the following questions:
If there are 25 deer at time $t=0$ and $t$ is measured in months, how long will it take for the number of deer to double?

What will be the limiting deer population?

Solution:

Below is the Python code block copy and pasted with the given differential equation and initial condition.

In[1]:
#@title Problem 1, solution with $P(0)=25$
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from scipy.integrate import solve_ivp
from ipywidgets import interact
import ipywidgets as widgets

# Define the differential equation
def dy_dx(x, y):
    return 0.0225*y-0.0003*y**2   #Here is where you input f(x,y) for the DE dy/dx = f(x,y)


# Define the solving/plotting function
def slope_plot(xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax, y_0):
  plt.figure()
  # Create a grid of points
  x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 20)
  y = np.linspace(ymin, ymax, 20)
  X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
  # Calculate the slope at each point
  U = np.ones_like(X)
  V = dy_dx(X, Y)
  # Normalize the vector <U,V> to be length 1
  N = np.sqrt(U**2 + V**2)
  U = U / N
  V = V / N
  #Solve numerically using solver from scipy
  sol = solve_ivp(dy_dx, (xmin,xmax), [y_0], t_eval=np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 200))
  #Plot slope field
  plt.quiver(X, Y, U, V, angles = 'xy')
  #Plot numerical solution satisfying y(0) = y_0
  plt.plot(sol.t,sol.y[0])
  plt.xlabel('x')
  plt.ylabel('y')
  plt.xlim(xmin, xmax)
  plt.ylim(ymin, ymax)
  plt.title('Slope field and solution satisfying $y(xmin)=y_0$')
  plt.show()

#Set up interactive widgets for various parameters
interact(slope_plot,
         xmin=widgets.FloatText(value=0,description='xmin:'),
         xmax=widgets.FloatText(value=300,description='xmax:'),
         ymin=widgets.FloatText(value=-5,description='ymin:'),
         ymax=widgets.FloatText(value=100,description='ymax:'),
         y_0=widgets.FloatText(value=25,description='y_0:')
         );

We see that the solution to the initial value problem

$$ \left\{ \begin{array}{rl} \dfrac{dP}{dt} &= 0.0225P - 0.0003 P^2 \\ P(0) &= 25 \end{array} \right. $$

satisfies (approximately) $P(60) = 50$, and so it has taken approximately 60 months, or 5 years, for the population to double from 25 to 50.

It appears that the limiting deer population is

$$\displaystyle \lim_{t \to \infty} P(t) = 75 \mbox{ deer},$$

which we'll learn how to determine in section 2.2 (equilibrium solutions and stability), but we can experiment and see that the solution satisfying $P(0) = 75$ is constant for all $t$.

Problem 2

A corporation maintains a balance of $B(t)$ (in millions of dollars) in an account, where $t$ is measured in years. Interest with a nominal annual rate of $2\%$ compounds continuously (that is, the rate at which interest is added to the account is proportional to $B$ with proportionality constant $0.02$ year$^{-1}$). In addition, the corporation continuously withdraws money from the account at a rate of $4$ million dollars per year.

Construct a slope field and appropriate solution curves to answer the following questions:

Describe what you think happens as $t$ increases if $B(0) = 300$.

Contrast this to the case if $B(0) = 100,$ being sure to explain in practical terms the difference between these cases.

Solution: Reading carefully, we set up the differential equation

$$\dfrac{dB}{dt} = 0.02B - 4,$$

where $B(t)$ is the balance in the account (in millions of dollars) at time $t$ (in years).

We can use the Python code to obtain the slope fields below.

$$ \left\{ \begin{array}{rl} \dfrac{dB}{dt} &= 0.02B - 4 \\ B(0) &= 300 \end{array} \right. $$

appears to increase without bound as $t$ increases. In practical terms, the money entering the account from interest outpaces the (constant) payments, so that the balance grows without bound.

Problem 3

A model for the voltage in a certain circuit is modeled by $$ \frac{dV}{dt} = -V(V-c)(V-5)$$

where $0 < c < 5$ is a control voltage.

Suppose that $c=1$. If $V(0) = 2,$ determine $\displaystyle \lim_{t \to \infty} V(t).$

Now suppose that $c=3$. Supposing we still have $V(0) = 2,$ determine $\displaystyle \lim_{t \to \infty} V(t).$

Solution:

For

$$ \left\{ \begin{array}{rl} \dfrac{dV}{dt} &= -V(V-1)(V-5)\\ V(0) &= 2 \end{array} \right. $$

it appears that

$$\lim_{t \to \infty} V(t) = 5.$$

When we discuss equilibrium solutions and stability in 2.2 we'll be obtaining conclusions like this from sign analysis, but we can quickly do "numerical experiments" like this with slope fields. The slope field for this case is below.
